subjects covered include a possible source manuscript for Malory's first tale; the "Arthuricity" of the little-known Latin romance Arthur and Gorlagon; images of sterility and fertility in the continuations of Chretien's Conte du Graal; and early modern responses to Geoffrey of Monmouth's account of Arthur's dealings withRome. Norris Lacy ranges widely over the evolution of the Arthurian legend, and Ronald Hutton considers representations of both Christian and pagan religion in modern novels and cinema. The volume ends with a bibliographical supplement on recent additions to Arthurian fiction. CONTRIBUTORS: Derek Brewer, Jonathan Passaro, Amanda Hopkins, Thomas Hinton, Sian Echard, Norris Lacy, Ronald Hutton, Raymond Thompson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aArchibald, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrewer, Derek S, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrewer, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEchard, Sian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEchard, Siân, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinton, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopkins, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutton, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, David F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLacy, Norris J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPassaro, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Raymond H, econtributor.4ctb4ht